  "summary": "Megan Barnard shares a memory of her mother's devastation following Betty's death, specifically noting that her mother bought stockings for Betty that she never got to use. This shared grief creates an emotional bond between Megan and Franklin Clarke. As the meeting progresses, Tora Grey shifts the focus to future planning, prompting Franklin to suggest that the group should join forces once a fourth letter arrives.\n\nHercule Poirot proposes several specific lines of inquiry to the group. He suggests an \"offensive strategy\" where Megan argues with a waitress named Milly Higley to provoke her into revealing her feelings about Betty, and he recommends that Donald Fraser show interest in the same waitress. For Mary DeLour, Poirot suggests interviewing children near her aunt's shop to see if they witnessed anyone entering. Tora Grey notes that the third letter was postmarked from Putney, suggesting the killer, ABC, is from London. Franklin Clarke proposes placing a provocative advertisement to attract ABC's attention, an idea Poirot deems worth trying. Franklin records the group's plan, which includes Megan and Donald interacting with Milly Higley, questioning the children of Andersson, and placing the advertisement.\n\nAfter the group disperses, Poirot reveals to Hastings that he manipulated the conversation to give the members a sense of purpose. He observes the interpersonal tensions, noting Franklin's rapport with Megan and Tora Grey's anger. Tora Grey later speaks with Poirot privately, explaining that she did not leave Compiegne willingly; she clarifies that while Franklin is loyal, it was the delusional Mrs. Clarke who insisted she leave the house due to irrational suspicion.",
